{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205696404/1930120301/0245.xml":{"full_text":"THE WEATHER\nFair and not juite ao cold today, lowest\ntemperature about* 32 degrees Thursday, partly\ncloudy. Moderate southwest winds. Tempera*\nture yesterday\u2014Highest, 28; lowest, 17.\nFull Weather Report on Page 4\nThe Washlnato\u00df rimes la the only afternoon neper In\nthis elty pnbliehlne the new* dispatches of International\nNews Service and Unlrenal Service.\nI\nRich Publisher Found Mysteriously Burned to Death\nHOOVER ASKS FOR 0. S. BUDGET OF 4 BILLIONS\nURGED FOR\nCAPITAL\u2019S\nNEEDS\nPresident Calls on Congress\nTo Practice Rigid Economy\nTo Keep Big Deficit Down\nComplete Budget\nNews on Page 18\nBy GEORGE R. HOLMES\nPresident Hoover sent the 1932\nbudget to Congress today with\nthe significant warning that\n\u201cthis is not a time when we can\nafford to embark upon any new\nor enlarged ventures of govero-\nThe expenses of operating the\nFederal Government for the next\nfiscal year were estimated at\n$3,932,842,411. or about $221,000,-\n000 greater than for the present\nfiscal year. despite falling Fed\nera! revenues because of the\nbusiness depression. The figure\nHoes hot include th \u2019deficit.\nTreasury Deficit\nThere WW tjfr-: fr.<fewtosur\u00bb deficit\nlately 8180.000.000, the Presi\ndent stated, and it will be held\nat that point by rigid economies,\nand by the application of some\n$185,000,000 in foreign interest\npayments to current expenses.\nUnder these conditions, the\nPresident stated that it was im\npossible to continue the 1 per\ner\u2019\u2019* income tax reduction granted\nby Congressional resolution last\nyear.\nThe President wrote:\n\u201cI regret that the present\noutlook for heavy decrease in\nprobable income (due to the\nbusiness depression) and the\nnecessity to- increase public\nworks and aid to employment\ndoes not warrant the continua\ntion of the reduction at the\npresent time.**\nA Reassuring Note\nNotwithstanding the present un\nfavorable state of the Treasury\u2019s\nfinances. Mr. Hoover informed\nCongress that he was submitting\n(Continued on Page 18, Col. 6)\nHere\u2019s Where\nFunds Go\nHere are the estimates of\nhow much it will take to\noperate some of the princi\npal departments of the Gov\nernment the next fiscal year\nas disclosed in the budget\nsent to Congress today:\nLegislative establishment\u2014\ns2B,B\u00df3,2B3.\nWhite House $473,000.\nFederal Farm Board\u2014\nslol,ooo,ooo.\nInterstate Commerce Com\nmission\u2014sll,97 5,593.\nU. 8. Shipping 80ard\u2014\n-539,406,000.\nU. S. Veterans Bureau (in\ncluding pensions)\u2014s946,2B9,-\n758.\nDepartment of Agriculture\n\u20145225,537,476.\nDepartment of Commerce\n\u2014554,638,226.\nDepartment of the Interior\n\u2014585,345,211.\nDepart:; ent of Lab or\u2014\n513,446,400.\nNavy Department\u2014s349,-\n628,298.\nPostoffice Department\n$735,003,057.\nState Department $17,-\n731,306.\nWar Department $464,-\n645,806.\nOnly the Navy and State\nDepartments were able to\nshave their estimates below\nthe expenditures of the pres\nent fiscal year.\nTIT? A OHP\u201d A Pulse-Tingling Tale Begin It Friday\nIKjEK HJLAK.L of the Underworld In The Times\ni '2 1 \u25a0\u25a0\u25a0J'p. I' 1\nSaves Home From Fire\nWK\niUMPk. /OM\nHr 1 R&wfew\nmW*\nU ft a\nini\nHf j\u00bbj|\nft' fl\nkJS Wihbi \u2019\u2019\u2019tS\nnn\nB i\n\nw\nW w WG\nw Hr\nfe\u00ae\nftk\nt- ajW'- x\nv\ns r ,4' Rfc. o S\n;\\V' W,-> W /i\nM lak<~>\u00bb\u00ab?'.\nwo\u00ae\n\u2014Times Staff Photo\nLOIS WHEELER\nATTEMPTING to carry a blazing towel through the\ndining room to the outside, Lois Wheeler, 12, of Takoma.\nPark, found herself engulfed in flames. She telephoned\na fire alarm and volunteer firemen responded in time\nto save the structure.\nGIRL, 12, SAVES\nBURNING HOME\nLois Wheeler, 12-year-old school\ngirl, today was acclaimed a\nheroine for her work in saving,\nher home in Takoma Park from\ndestruction by fire late yesterday\nand for having seen that an in\nvalid member of the family was\ncarried to safety.\nThe girl, daughter of R. B.\nWheeler, was in the kitchen of\nthe family home, 75 Flower Ave.,\nwhen the fire started. After\nvainly attempting to beat out the\nflames, she called neighbors who\ncarried Miss Eleanor Pancost, an\ninvalid, to safety.\nLois then called the Silver\nSpring and Takoina Park fire de\npartments. The house was dam\naged about SBOO.\nmrsTbevins HOPS\nNEW YORK, Dec. 3 (1.N.5.).\nMrs. Martha Bevins hopped from\nNorth Beach airport today in an\nattempt to better the transcon\ntinental women\u2019s flight record re\ncently set by Miss Ruth Nichols.\nNO. 15,40?\u201c\"\nBUDGETSHOWS\nGAIN FOR D.G.\nThe District pf Columbia esti\nmates for the fiscal year of 1932,\nsubmitted to Congress today by\nPresident Hoover, make a total\nof $47,796,047.\nAlthough this is a decrease of\n$601,385 from appropriations for\nthe current year, the new budget\nrepresents in the main substantial\nincreases for many departments\nof the municipal government, and\nis regarded as one of the most\nliberal group of estimates that has\ncome from the Budget Bureau in\nseveral years.\nSeeming Cut Explained\nThe seeming cut in the local\nestimates is due largely to the fact\nthat the $3,000,000 appropriated\nby Congress for the purchase of\nland for the Municipal Center\nproject for the current year does\nnot recur in J 932.\nDeducting this amount from the\nbydget\u2014and also $65,000 for the\ncompletion of designs for build\nings in the Municipal center\u2014the\n\n(Continued on Page 2, Col. 4)\nDavis Campaign Fund Defended\nRICH PUBLISHER\nBURNS, DIES IN\nN. I. FIRE\nCourtland H. Young, Famous\nIn Divorce Annals, Found\nOn 7th Floor of His Home\nNEW YORK, Dec 3 (LNE.).\nCourtland H, Young, magazine\npublisher, was burned to death in\nhis apartment on West llfty-fifth\nStreet today.\nFiremen who were called to\nextinguish the fire found the\nbody of the rich man, who was\nbom 54 years ago in New Orleans.\nThe circumstances surrounding\nthe finding of the body of the\nwealthy publisher puzzled police.\nThe fire in the victim\u2019s apart\nment was not serious, and detec-1\ntives said they did not believe it\nwas a large enough blaze for a\nman to bum to death.\nOccurred on 7th Floor\nPolice officially announced they\nwere investigating certain mys\nterious details in connection with\nthe tragedy. An autopsy on the\nbody Win probably be nmfumred\nThe fire occurred on the\nseventh floor of Young\u2019s apart\nment at 110 West 55th St. Fire\nmen had put out the blaze, and\nwere \u201cmopping up\u2019\u2019 when they\naccidentally stumbled over the\nbody.\nHowever, another tenant was\novercome by smoke from the sue\nand treated by an ambulance\nsurgeon.\nIn Numerous Suits\nThe marital tribulations of the\nYoungs kept the divorce courts in\nNew York and New Jersey busy\nfor two years or more. I\nSuit and counter suit were fol-1\nlowed by reconciliations and\nfurther suits. Mrs. Young\ncharged her husband with cruelty\nand drunkenness.\nYoung, in turn, charged her\nwith corrupting the morals of\ntheir eight-year-old daughter, Rose\nbelle (\u201cRosebud\u201d), by failing to\nwear sufficient clothing in the\nhouse.\nYoung added another Item to\nhis complaint against his wife\nwhen he denied he was the\nfather of Neal Campbell Young,\nwho was 2 years old at the time.\nThe publisher was granted a\ndivorce from the stage beauty\nin December of 1928\nDrought Relief Cut\nUrged by Sec. Hyde\nA feed and seed loan of $25,-\n000,000, instead of $60,000,000, to\nfarmers in the drought-stricken\nareas of the country was pro\nposed to Congress today by Sec\nretary of Agriculture Hyde He\nsent the draft of a bill covering\nthis amount to Representative\nHaugen (R.) of lowa, chairman\ncf the House Agriculture Com\nmittee.\nThe $60,000,000 hitherto pro\nposed is contained in legislation\nintroduced by Senator Robinson\n(D.) of Arkansas and Represen\ntative Aswell (D.) of Louisiana.\nWorkers Aid Dog, Trapped\nIn Pipe on Fox Hunt\nLURAY, Va., Dec. 3.\u2014Fox\nhunting may be great sport, but\nits hard on the town\u2019s water\nsupply.\nSunday, a hound was pursuing\na' fox in the foothills of the Blue\nRidge, five miles east of here\nThe hunted beast, seeking refuge,\nran into a 10-inch water pipe used\nfor conveying water from the\nintake into the reservoir.\nThe water was shut dowh at\nthe time and the fox sped down\nthe pipe, followed by the hound.\nWEDNESDAY, DECEMBER 3, 1930\nHead South \u2014To Fight Prohibition\nR *l\u00ae HL. H H\n\"SI T\nmt jh <m JBE-jya\nmMHHHBMBak SL Jr\nMraMr z IL ft SK' An nn 1\nMl J\ns\ni c x tr v B Sil k wft 1 1\n\u2014lnternational Newsreai\nANTIPROHIBITIONISTS OFF TO PARLEY\nDELEGATES to the Women\u2019s National Prohibition Reform Convention are shown\nleaving New York for Louisville, Ky. Those pictured are Miss Eva Hoyt, Mrs. A. S.\nMather, Mrs. Charles H. Sabin, Mrs. Cortland Nichols, Mrs. William Putnam and Miss\nLouise Marion.\nIOWA RENAMED\nLOGAN CIRCLE\nThe Senate this afternoon\npassed a bill changing the name\nof lowa Circle, on Thirteenth\nStreet, to Logan Circle. The bill\nhad already passed the House\nand niow goes to the President\nfor his signature.\nThrough the change in aame,\nCongress recognizes the Civil War\nservices of Gen. John A. Logan,\nwhose statue stands in the circle.\nThe Logan Circle bill was the\nOnly District measure on the\ncalendar of the Senate which was\nacted upon 'today. The District\nhas about a dozen bills on the\ncalendar, but all were passed for\nfuture consideration.\nIncluded in measures holding\nover are the local law-enforce\nment measure, the bill providing\nfor merger of the street com\npanies and for the merger of the\ngas companies, and the bill gov\nerning court procedure in public\nutility cases.\nThe dog finally stuck in the\npipe, and whether or not the fox,\nbeing smaller, escaped is not\nknown.\nThe barking of the trapped dog\nwas heard and a gang of work\nmen were summoned to clear the\npipe. The sound died away how\never, and now the workmen will\nhave to open the two mile pipe to\nremove the trapped dog and per\nhaps the fox.\nScores of citizens are assisting\nin the work of opening the pipe.\nFascists Net\nU.S. Woirian\nIn Plot\nROME, Dec. 3 (1.N.5.).\u2014\nTwenty-six* persons, including sev\neral newspaper men, officials of\nthe cities of Milan and Rome, and\nothers prominent in social life in\nthe two cities were arrested to\nday on charges of belonging to\norganizations which plotted\nagainst the lives of Fascist lead\ners, it was officially announced.\nAn American woman, Mrs. Lil\nlian Vernon De Bosis, former\nresident of Boston and St. Louis,\nwas reported among those ques\ntioned, but her name was not\nincluded in the official announce\nment.\nHawks Leaves N. Y.\nOn Memphis Flight\nROOSEVELT FIELD, N. Y.,\nDec. 3 (I.N.S.).\u2014Capt. Frank\nHawks left here at 10:47 a. m.\ntoday on a non-stop flight to\nMemphis, Tenn., more than 1,000\nmiles.\nThe holder of the transconti\nnental non-stop record expected\nto take between five and six\nhours. Weather reports indicated\nhe would encounter slight head\nwinds.\nIn The Times Today\nPage\nComics 26\nDramatics 14\nFashion News 12,13\nFinancial New5....27, 28, 29\nMagazine Page 22\nRadio\nSociety 12. 13\nSports 23, 24, 25\nBudget Page 1$\nTHREE CENTS\nPITTS OBTAINED\nCASH, CLAIM\nJohn S. Farquhar, another of\nthe prosecution\u2019s outstanding wit\nnesses in the $5,000,000 embezzle\nment and conspiracy trial of\nthree former F. H. Smith Com\npany officials, took the witness\nstand in criminal division of the\nDistrict Supreme Court today.\nHis testimony dealt with the\nfinding of several boxes of books\nand papers of check manipula\ntions, which terminated in de\nposits to the personal account of\nJ. Bryan Pitts, one of the defend\nants, at the Southern Maryland\nTrust Company at Seat Pleasant,\nMd.\nFeared Loss of Job\nMr. Farquhar testified that be\nfore he left the employ of the\nSmith Company, he signed a\nstatement at the request of Mr.\nPitts denying the finding of the\nrecords and papers. He stated\nthat he did this because he\nfeared that he would lose his job\nif he refused.\nThe witness declared that on\nmore than 30 occasions at tjie\nrequest of C. Elbert Anadale, an\nother defendant, he cashed checks\nof the Smith Company made pay\nable to \u201ccash\u201d and generally rang\ning in amounts from SI,OOO to\n$3,000.\nOn other occasions, the witness\ntestified, h. cashed numerous\nchecks made payable to a dozen\nsubsidiary corporations of the\ncompany and indorsed by an of\nficer of the corporation, at the\ndirection of Mr. Anadale.\nTo Pitts\u2019 Account\nThe sums obtained in cashing\nboth of these kinds of checks,\nMr. Farquhar said, were taken to\nthe Southern Maryland Trust\nCompany end deposited to Mr.\nPitts\u2019 account. The usual deposit,\nhe said, to Mr. Pitts\u2019 account was\nSIO,OOO.\nEDITION\nAIDETERMS\n$500,000 AS\nffI\u2019SUM\nVauclain\u2019s Assistant Quizzed\nBy Senators on Amount\nSpent by Penna. Victor\nHalf a million dollars would\nbe a \u201cvery fair\u201d estimate of the\nmoney expended on behalf of the\nDavis-Brown ticket in the Penn\nsylvania primary last May, the'\nSenate campaign funds investi\ngating committee was informed\ntoday by one of the political\nmanagers for Sen. James J.\nDavis and Francis Shunk Brown,\ndefeated gubernatorial candidate.\nWilliam R. Douglas, assistant\nto Samuel Vauclain, who was di\nrecting the campaign for the\nDavis-Brown ticket, was the wit\nness. He was asked:\nHard to Estimate\n\u201cHow much was spent fat\nDavis?\u201d\n\u201cThat would \u00bbe hard to de\ntermine.\u2019*\n\"Would the expenditures have\nbeen as great if Davis had not\nbeen on the ticket?\u201d\n\u201cYes.\u201d\n\u201cWould they have been as\ngreat if Davis had been running\nalone?\"\n\"They would have been if\nthere had been a contest.\u201d\nMiss Earhart Hops;\nNuptials Reporter\nTtEWMKK.. N. J.,Dec. 3 (1.N.5.).\nAmelia Earhart, noted aviatrix,\na\u00bbnd George Palmer Putnam, pub\nlisher, who were reported recently\nto have obtained a marriage\nlicense, today left Newark Airport\nin a monoplane, with Miss- Ear\nhart piloting the plane. They\nwere accompanied by another\nwoman whose identity was not\nrevealed.\nWhile it was announced that\nMiss Earhart and Putnam were\nflying to Cleveland \u201con a business\ntrip,\u201d a friend of Miss Earhart\nsaid they were going to Cleveland\nto be married.\nDenatured Alcohol\nBlamed in 10 Deaths\nHARRISBURG, Dec. 3 (IN.S\nDeath toll from denatured alco\nhol used during a week-end cele\nbration among negroes here to\nday was 10, with another be\nlieved to be dying.\nCoroner Howard Milliken said\ndenatured alcohol has been used\nas a drink for some time by\nnegroes, who had been burning\nor boiling the liquid before drink\ning in an effort to eliminate\npoisons.\nChristmas\nSavings\nChecks\n\nSpend your savings\nwisely. Plan what\nyou want to give\nand decide where to\nbuy it before start\ning your shopping\ntour. Gift sugges\ntions for all are\nlisted today in\u2014\nWisteGift\nSuggestions\u201d","height":"30178","width":"24217"}}
